{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"05acbcdc-f92f-4bf3-b7a9-8980630c735e","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01Tz6ZpQQXSWDHmoxFAPo9G8","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Exploring repository context"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_018RCTdJzMJgwV3YMPXi8AxB","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /tmp/sv-d38efdfede204941a4d773a51f3b1c57/ 2>/dev/null; echo \"---\"; find /tmp/sv-d38efdfede204941a4d773a51f3b1c57/ -maxdepth 2 -type f 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check working directory contents","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check working directory contents"}],"interactionId":"0bee3f48-75de-4f65-abc0-4cae4830167f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` installed at `/opt/tools/createdump`. Let me look at what's in the current working directory first, then provide the configuration.\n\nFor .NET NativeAOT crash dumps, the key environment variables are:\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` - enables automatic crash dump generation\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` - full dump (MiniDumpWithFullMemory)\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` - path/pattern for dump files\n\n\n- `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics=1` - optional diagnostics\n- `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` - custom path to createdump tool\n\nI need to reconsider this for NativeAOT specifically. The managed runtime crash dump infrastructure works differently with NativeAOT since the runtime is compiled in. Starting from .NET 8, NativeAOT has better crash dump support, but .NET 11 might have different capabilities or requirements than what I initially outlined.\n\nFor NativeAOT crash dumps, the key variables are `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` to enable them, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` to control the dump size (with 4 being a full dump), and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` to specify where dumps get written. The `createdump` tool handles the actual dump generation, and you can point to it with `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`. There's also `DOTNET_EnableCrashReport=1` which generates a JSON crash report alongside the dump file.\n\nNow I'm thinking about what the user needs to configure in Kubernetes to make this work.","outputTokens":802,"requestId":"9816:18FEB2:594046F:61C2961:69F406B0"},"id":"898589f9-2e2d-45e5-819f-acfdc8204d71","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:49:54.374Z","parentId":"785ca1a5-e2c3-4bd5-b1ec-eb4f3282d26f"}
